In [25]:
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose
import pandas as pd

# Specify the period of the time series
period = 12

# Convert the fpt data into a Pandas Series
fpt_series = pd.Series(fpt.values)

# Decompose the time series using the seasonal_decompose() function
result = seasonal_decompose(fpt_series, model='multiplicative', period=period)

# Plot the decomposed time series
fig = result.plot()
fig.set_size_inches(16, 12)

Choose (d) : Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test, Graph¶

Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test¶

The null hypothesis of the ADF test is that the time series is non-stationary. So, if the p-value of the test is less than the significance level (0.05) then reject the null hypothesis and infer that the time series is indeed stationary.

In [18]:
result = adfuller(fpt)
print('ADF Statistic: {}'.format(result[0]))
print('p-value: {}'.format(result[1]))
print('Critical Values:')
for key, value in result[4].items():
    print('\t{}: {}'.format(key, value))

ADF Statistic: -2.7266819888433047
p-value: 0.06953382657356559
Critical Values:
	1%: -3.4439615820186846
	5%: -2.8675425624806605
	10%: -2.5699671340268937

So, in our case, if P Value > 0.05 we go ahead with finding the order of differencing.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

plt.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize':(9,7), 'figure.dpi':120})

# Original Series
fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(3)
ax1.plot(fpt.values); ax1.set_title('Original Series'); ax1.axes.xaxis.set_visible(False)

# 1st Differencing
ax2.plot(pd.Series(fpt.values).diff()); ax2.set_title('1st Order Differencing'); ax2.axes.xaxis.set_visible(False)

# 2nd Differencing
ax3.plot(pd.Series(fpt.values).diff().diff()); ax3.set_title('2nd Order Differencing')
plt.show()

from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Load the time series data
fpt = fpt 
# Define the figure size and DPI
plt.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize':(12,5), 'figure.dpi':120})
# Perform first-order differencing
diff1 = pd.Series(fpt.values).diff().dropna()
# Create a 1x3 grid of subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3)
# Plot the first-order differencing
axes[0].plot(diff1); axes[0].set_title('1st Order Differencing')
# Plot the PACF for the first-order differencing
plot_pacf(diff1, ax=axes[1], lags=25)
# Plot the ACF for the first-order differencing
plot_acf(diff1, ax=axes[2], lags=25)
# Adjust the spacing between the subplots
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.4)
# Show the plot
plt.show()

from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Load the time series data
fpt = fpt

# Define the figure size and DPI
plt.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize':(12,5), 'figure.dpi':120})

# Perform second-order differencing
diff2 = pd.Series(fpt.values).diff().diff().dropna()

# Create a 1x3 grid of subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3)

# Plot the second-order differencing
axes[0].plot(diff2); axes[0].set_title('2nd Order Differencing')

# Plot the PACF for the second-order differencing
plot_pacf(diff2, ax=axes[1], lags=25)

# Plot the ACF for the second-order differencing
plot_acf(diff2, ax=axes[2], lags=25)

# Adjust the spacing between the subplots
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.4)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Build the ARIMA Model¶

ARIMA(4,1,5)¶

In [41]:
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

# Create Training and Test
train = fpt.values
test = pd.read_excel('fpt_test_10.xlsx')

# Build Model
model415 = ARIMA(train, order=(4, 1, 5))  
fitted = model415.fit()  

# Forecast
start = len(train) # starting index for test data
end = start + len(test) - 1 # ending index for test data

x = fitted.get_forecast(steps=len(test), alpha=0.05).summary_frame()  # 95% confidence interval
fc = x['mean'] 
lower = x['mean_ci_lower']
upper = x['mean_ci_upper']

# Make as pandas series
test.index = pd.RangeIndex(start=499, stop=499+len(test), step=1)
fc.index = pd.RangeIndex(start=499, stop=499+len(fc), step=1)
fc_series = pd.Series(fc)



lower_series = pd.Series(lower)
lower_series.index = pd.RangeIndex(start=499, stop=499+len(lower_series), step=1)

upper_series = pd.Series(upper)
upper_series.index = pd.RangeIndex(start=499, stop=499+len(upper_series), step=1)

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5), dpi=100)
plt.plot(train, label='training')

plt.plot(test, label='actual')
plt.plot(fc_series, label='forecast')

plt.fill_between(lower_series.index, lower_series, upper_series, 
                 color='k', alpha=.15)
plt.title('Forecast vs Actuals')
plt.legend(loc='upper left', fontsize=8)
plt.show()

In [39]:
# Fit an ARIMA(4,1,5) model
model = model415
model_fit = model415.fit()

# Get the AR and MA coefficients
ar_coefs = model_fit.arparams
ma_coefs = model_fit.maparams

# Compute the roots
ar_roots = np.roots(np.concatenate(([1], -ar_coefs), axis=0))
ma_roots = np.roots(np.concatenate(([1], ma_coefs), axis=0))

# Create unit circles
theta = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 1000)
x = np.cos(theta)
y = np.sin(theta)

# Plot the AR roots and unit circle on the left
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12,6))
axs[0].plot(x, y, 'k--', label='Unit Circle')
axs[0].scatter(ar_roots.real, ar_roots.imag, marker='o', color='r', label='AR Roots')
axs[0].set_aspect('equal')
axs[0].set_xlabel('Real')
axs[0].set_ylabel('Imaginary')
axs[0].set_title('AR Unit Circle Plot of ARIMA(4,1,5) Model')
axs[0].legend()

# Plot the MA roots and unit circle on the right
axs[1].plot(x, y, 'k--', label='Unit Circle')
axs[1].scatter(ma_roots.real, ma_roots.imag, marker='o', color='b', label='MA Roots')
axs[1].set_aspect('equal')
axs[1].set_xlabel('Real')
axs[1].set_ylabel('Imaginary')
axs[1].set_title('MA Unit Circle Plot of ARIMA(4,1,5) Model')
axs[1].legend()

plt.show()

start = len(train) # starting index for test data
end = start + len(test) - 1 # ending index for test data

x = fitted.get_forecast(steps=len(test), alpha=0.05).summary_frame()  # 95% confidence interval
fc = x['mean'] 
lower = x['mean_ci_lower']
upper = x['mean_ci_upper']

# Make as pandas series
test.index = pd.RangeIndex(start=499, stop=499+len(test), step=1)
fc.index = pd.RangeIndex(start=499, stop=499+len(fc), step=1)
fc_series = pd.Series(fc)



lower_series = pd.Series(lower)
lower_series.index = pd.RangeIndex(start=499, stop=499+len(lower_series), step=1)

upper_series = pd.Series(upper)
upper_series.index = pd.RangeIndex(start=499, stop=499+len(upper_series), step=1)

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5), dpi=100)
plt.plot(train, label='training')

plt.plot(test, label='actual')
plt.plot(fc_series, label='forecast')

plt.fill_between(lower_series.index, lower_series, upper_series, 
                 color='k', alpha=.15)
plt.title('Forecast vs Actuals')
plt.legend(loc='upper left', fontsize=8)
plt.show()

# Fit an ARIMA(4,2,5) model
model = model425
model_fit = model425.fit()

# Get the AR and MA coefficients
ar_coefs = model_fit.arparams
ma_coefs = model_fit.maparams

# Compute the roots
ar_roots = np.roots(np.concatenate(([1], -ar_coefs), axis=0))
ma_roots = np.roots(np.concatenate(([1], ma_coefs), axis=0))

# Create unit circles
theta = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 1000)
x = np.cos(theta)
y = np.sin(theta)

# Plot the AR roots and unit circle on the left
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12,6))
axs[0].plot(x, y, 'k--', label='Unit Circle')
axs[0].scatter(ar_roots.real, ar_roots.imag, marker='o', color='r', label='AR Roots')
axs[0].set_aspect('equal')
axs[0].set_xlabel('Real')
axs[0].set_ylabel('Imaginary')
axs[0].set_title('AR Unit Circle Plot of ARIMA(4,2,5) Model')
axs[0].legend()

# Plot the MA roots and unit circle on the right
axs[1].plot(x, y, 'k--', label='Unit Circle')
axs[1].scatter(ma_roots.real, ma_roots.imag, marker='o', color='b', label='MA Roots')
axs[1].set_aspect('equal')
axs[1].set_xlabel('Real')
axs[1].set_ylabel('Imaginary')
axs[1].set_title('MA Unit Circle Plot of ARIMA(4,2,5) Model')
axs[1].legend()

plt.show()
